2026-04-21 02:46:34 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ctrl1_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl2_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl3_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl4_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl5_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl6_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl7_switch_indicator_led_holder', 'ctrl8_switch_indicator_led_holder'] hypothesis_explanation='The root cause appears to be that all switch indicator (control module) LEDs are physically missing from their holders, so there is an open circuit at each indicator LED position. In this design, each control indicator LED and its resistor is in parallel to the main switch path. If the holder is empty and not internally shunted, the parallel branch is open, but the main path for lamp current should pass through the switches and not require the indicator LED to be present for the lamp to work. However, if the LED holders are wired such that missing LEDs leave the circuit open (i.e., the circuit is not completed unless an LED is present in the holder), then this would interrupt the main 12V line. All eight holders are missing their indicator LEDs and cannot be replaced, so the likely persistent fault is open circuits at these eight holders due to missing LEDs. This interrupts continuity from the battery to the load module.'
